In <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../220/25220.xml">
quantum computing</link>, a <b>charge qubit</b> is a <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../884/26884.xml">
superconducting</link> <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../284/25284.xml">
qubit</link>  whose <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../638/279638.xml#xpointer(//*[./st=%22Basis+states%22])">
basis states</link> are charge states (ie. states which represent the presence or absence of excess <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../845/376845.xml">
Cooper pairs</link> in the island).  A charge qubit is formed by a tiny <link>
superconducting island</link> (also known as a <link>
Cooper-pair box</link>) coupled by a <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../712/446712.xml">
Josephson junction</link> to a superconducting reservoir (see figure).  The state of the qubit is determined by the number of Cooper pairs which have tunneled across the junction. In contrast with the charge state of an atomic or molecular ion, the charge states of such an "island" involve a macroscopic number of conduction electrons of the island. The quantum superposition of charge states can be achieved by tuning the gate voltage U that controls the chemical potential of the island. The charge qubit is typically read-out by electrostatically coupling the island to an extremely sensitive <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../364/40364.xml">
electrometer</link> such as the <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../852/42852.xml">
radio-frequency</link> <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../700/2133700.xml">
single-electron transistor</link>.<p>

Typical T1 times for a charge qubit are on the order of 1-2 μs.</p>

